{
  "style": "",
  "texts": [
    "Different from the Reinforcement Learning with verifiable reward (RLVR) setting, where the outcome reward R(q, o) can be directly computed via hard-coded scripts such as unit tests for code generation or string matching for math answers, rubric-based RL requires a more sophisticated rewarding system to get the sequence-level reward R(q, o, r): (a) For each prompt q, it corresponds to a unique set of criteria r = {r i } d i=1 to measure whether a response fully follows the instructions specified in q; (b) Given prompt q, response o, and rubric r, we use an LLM (rubric verifier) to judge whether the response o satisfies each rubric r i extracted from the prompt q.",
    "As we shall see later, we observe that naively prompting an off-the-shelf LLM as the rubric verifier does not yield the best result, which motivates us to finetune an LLM to this task.",
    "Based on the formulation above, we describe the details of each component in our RIFL pipeline as follows.",
    "In Section 4.2, we introduce a synthetic rubric generation pipeline to construct a high-quality training set D of prompts paired with rubrics.",
    "In Section 4.3, we develop methods to train a rubric verifier to provide R(q, o, r) which outperforms prompted LLM judges."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}